<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Fourth defense of the year. First one that's a negotiation, not a Q&A.</p>
  <p>Unit 5's close-out day. Three things land in 80 minutes. <strong>First (~10 min): submission.</strong> Your <a href="/units/unit-5/assessment-water-stakeholders/">Stakeholders Map + Position Paper</a> + final <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Doc</a> reflection get submitted at the start of class. Five weeks of work lands. <strong>Second (~55 min): the Stakeholder Roundtable.</strong> Students cluster into roundtables of ~6-8, ideally with one stakeholder per case represented at each table — a delta farmer + an upstream farmer + a city consumer + a downstream community + an environmental NGO + a government rep — six legitimate positions in genuine disagreement. The format is <strong>negotiation, not Q&A</strong>: stakeholders speak <em>to each other</em>, not to a moderator-audience. Each opens with their statement. Then the table tries to negotiate — looking for points of legitimate compromise without abandoning core stances. Pre-recorded video Roundtable for students who chose that option in Block 8. <strong>Third (~15 min): debrief + unit close.</strong> Did any roundtable reach consensus (rare and worth noticing — most real water disputes don't)? Where did legitimate compromise emerge? Where did the table hit irreducible disagreement? Then the unit-close reflection — one claim, one question, one connection.</p>
  <p>Higher-stakes defense format than U1's NASA Committee, U2's planning-audience share-out, or U4's Policy Panel — those were all "one speaker, audience asks questions." Today's negotiation muscle is what U6 (Biosphere & Land Use) uses next. The skill compounds.</p>
</section>

