<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">🛠️ Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All paths put you at a Roundtable for the C-strand score. The path you pick is about the format you committed to in Block 8.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I can defend my stakeholder's position under multi-directional pressure, accurately summarize a competing stakeholder's position, and identify a possible point of compromise without abandoning my core stance.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Live Roundtable participation (default — most students)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">You're at one of the ~4-5 live Roundtables. ~6-8 students per table, one stakeholder per case (or close to it). Round 1: each stakeholder opens with their 60-sec statement. Round 2-3: open negotiation — propose, challenge, concede, refuse, counter-propose. Mr. Ignash floats. Each table captures its own one-paragraph debrief at the end: where did legitimate compromise emerge, where did irreducible disagreement land.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Group · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Pre-recorded video Roundtable + peer-feedback role at a live table (stretch)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">For students whose video alt-format was pre-approved with Mr. Ignash and finalised in Block 8. Submit the video Roundtable to Classroom by the start of class. Then sit at one live Roundtable as a structured peer-feedback observer — watch for the negotiation moves (concession, refusal, counter-proposal) and write one specific suggestion per stakeholder for their post-Roundtable reflection.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo + group · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Observer-recorder warm-up before joining (choice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If your Roundtable feels heavy and a warm-up would help, observe one other table for ~15 minutes before joining your own. Take notes on what the negotiation moves <em>look like</em> in practice — that's good rehearsal data for your own table. Useful especially for students whose case has 7-8 stakeholders crowding one table.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Alt-format finalisation (practice / safety-net)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If your deliverable isn't fully ready by start of class — Position Paper not submitted, video Roundtable not recorded — talk to Mr. Ignash immediately. The safety-net path is a 1:1 conversation in the back of the room while live Roundtables run, with submission and a recorded short defense by end of class. Don't disappear; come find Mr. Ignash.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Safety-net</span>
