<section class="block-section concepts" style="margin-top:24px;">
  <span class="section-tag">🔭 Preview — Unit 6</span>
  <h2>Where we go next</h2>
  <p>Unit 6 asks: <strong>how do you allocate land when every stakeholder wants something different from the same hectare?</strong> Land and water decisions are entangled all the way down — a Cauvery delta farmer's water claim is also a land-use claim (the rice paddies that need the water occupy the land), and an upstream Karnataka farmer's water claim is also a land-use claim (the sugarcane that drinks the water occupies the land too). U6 (Biosphere & Land Use) widens the scope from water alone to whole-landscape multi-stakeholder planning. The case anchors shift — coastal mangroves vs. industrial development, peri-urban farmland vs. housing expansion, forest commons vs. plantation conversion, peri-urban grazing vs. solar arrays — but the perspective-taking muscle is identical to what U5 just built. Same Stakeholders Map shape. Same voice-match T/T gate. Same negotiation-not-Q&A defense format.</p>
  <p>The frameworks from this unit (OPVL on tribunal documents + Hindu articles + AI summaries, the 7-field Stakeholders Map, the four-part Position Paper, the AI Documentation discipline, the Stakeholder Voice rehearsal) carry forward intact. If something felt shaky in U5, the <a href="/foundations/">Foundations</a> pages stay live all year — and the <a href="/units/unit-5/">Unit 5 landing</a> isn't going anywhere either. The Cauvery dispute you spent five weeks understanding doesn't disappear from your map; it becomes the substrate U6 builds on.</p>
</section>
